Oscar-winning actress Lupita Nyong’o will star in Born a Crime, the film adaptation of The Daily Show host Trevor Noah’s bestselling autobiography The star, who played Nakia in Marvel’s Black Panther, will co-produce the biopic and play Noah’s mother, Patricia. According to the reports, the film doesn’t yet have a director attached to it. Trevor Noah’s memoir – Born a Crime: Stories From a South African Childhood (Spiegel & Grau) – was released in 2016. The memoir details Noah’s life with his mother, who embodied resilience and tenacity as she raised her mixed-race child during apartheid in South Africa. READ MORE: I’m excited to tell a real African story – Lupita on her new film The Black Panther star shared the exciting development with her followers on social media, posting an image of herself with Noah. She wrote: “When I read Trevor Noah’s Born a Crime, I could not put the book down. Excited to announce that I will be starring in and producing its feature film adaptation!” Noah responded to the announcement through Instagram. He reposted the same image and wrote: “My mum is a powerful woman who could easily be one of the beautiful soldiers in Wakanda. So it’s beyond a perfect fit that she would be portrayed on the big screen by the radiant and regal Lupita Nyong’o. I’m beyond excited.”  Additional reporting by EWN